@node Introduction "SetSysTime - Introduction"

@{b}@{fg shine} Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}

I've  had  the  problem  that I own an Amiga A1000 with a HD and no battery
backed  clock  and  an  A600HD  with  a  defect  battery  backed clock.  So
everytime  I  made  a  coldstart,  the systemtime was reseted to the date I
installed  the HD :-(.  The AmigaDOS 1.3 command @{b}DATE@{ub} is very uncomfortable
and  the  GUI-Tool  I  used  in  the earlier days (called "TimeSet") always
defaults  to  the  current system time (which is set to a date in the early
90'th after a coldstart of my A1000).

I  decided  to  write  my own tool with a GUI somehow simular to the OS 3.x
@{b}TIME@{ub} comand -- just better ;-).

The  time displayed in this Dialog at startup is the time of the last boot.
So  usually  --  if  your  Amiga runs every day as mine -- you just have to
@{i}click @{ui} on the next day of the displayed calendar and adjust the sliders for
the clock to set the current time.

The  time  of  the  last  boot is stored as filetime of a file specified as
argument,  i.e.   the  time  of  the  last  (write-)access  of that file is
changed, not the contents of the file. Look at the section @{" Usage " link Usage} for more
details.

This  tool  is  @{b}freeware@{ub}  but feel free to send me any donations or just an
email so I know that there is someone using this tool. 
@endnode

@node Requirements "SetSysTime - Requirements"

@{b}@{fg shine} Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}

You need an Amiga ;-)
I  think  this  software  would also run with an emulated Amiga but I think
every  emulated  Amiga  has a battery backed real-time clock (borrowed from
the host system) so there is no usage for this tool.

This  tool  makes  only  sence  if  you @{b}don't@{ub} have a working battery backed
real-time clock, like a plain A1000, A500, or A600.

It should run with every AmigaOS and any CPU.  The dialog is font-sensitive
(uses  the  default font) and is optimized to open on any screen regardless
of  the  used  screenmode.   Nevertheless  there  might  be  problems  if a
non-native screen is used (i.e.  if a gfx-card is used).

I have tested this software with the following systems:

  - A1000, CPU 68000, OS 1.2 and 1.3
  - A600, CPU 68030, OS 3.1
  - A3000T, CPU 68040, OS 3.1
@endnode

@node Installation "SetSysTime - Installation"

@{b}@{fg shine} Installation@{fg text}@{ub}

Installation is very easy so I haven't written an installer-script for this
purpose (and there is no Installer available for AmigaOS 1.2 or 1.3):

Just copy the file "SetSysTime" to any directory that is in your searchpath
(usually into the directory "C:").

Chose  a  file  that  should  be  used for storing the date and time as its
filetime  or  create  a  new  file  for this purpose, e.g.  by entering the
following command into a shell:

   @{b}echo >S:.Date "Used for SetSysTime, don't change or delete."@{ub}

Use your favorite editor to add the following line to your startup-sequence
just  before  the  lines  calling the "user-startup" or the line containing
"LoadWB":

	@{b}SetSysTime S:.Date load@{ub}

where  "@{b}S:.Date@{ub}" might be replaced by the path and filename of the file you
want to use for storing the time.
@endnode

@node Usage "SetSysTime - Usage"

@{b}@{fg shine} Usage@{fg text}@{ub}
The  usage  of  the  tool is very easy and intuitiv.  You could either call
this tool from @{" CLI " link CLIStart} or via the @{" Workbench " link WBStart}.

The dialog is described @{" here " link Dialog}.

@endnode

@node CLIStart "SetSysTime - Usage"

@{b}@{fg shine} Start from CLI@{fg text}@{ub}

Usually  the  tool  is called from the commandline (CLI) with the following
arguments:

   @{b}FILE/A,GUI/T,LOAD/S,SAVE/S@{ub}


@{b}@{fg shine} FILE@{fg text}@{ub}

This argument is used to pass the filename (including the path) of the file
that  should  be  used to store the date into respectively read the date of
the last boot from.
The  date  is read and stored in the filedate of the file, i.e. the date of
the  last  (write-)access  to  the  file.   The contents of the file is not
changed so you may use the file "startup-sequence" for this purpose.  But I
recommend  to  use a file created just for this purpose as mentioned in the
chapter @{" Installation " link Installation}.

This argument is required.


@{b}@{fg shine} GUI@{fg text}@{ub}

This  is  a  toggle used to indicate whether the dialog should be opened or
not.  If you want to supress the opening of the dialog you have to set this
argument to "@{b}off@{ub}", "@{b}false@{ub}", or "@{b}no@{ub}" (see for examples at the bottom of this
page).
This argument is only useful if you also pass the argument "@{b}SAVE@{ub}" or "@{b}LOAD@{ub}".


@{b}@{fg shine} LOAD@{fg text}@{ub}

This  switch  is  used to indicate whether the dialog should be initialized
using  the  current  system time or the time of the last boot stored in the
filetime of the specified file.
If  "@{b}SetSysTime@{ub}"  is  called  from the "startup-sequence" to set the system
clock  after  a coldstart this switch should be set.  If the tool is called
after the startup  (e.g. to store the current system time before the system
is powered down) this argument must not be passed.


@{b}@{fg shine} SAVE@{fg text}@{ub}
This  switch  indicates  whether  the  system  time should be stored in the
filetime of the specified file or not.  If the dialog is opened this switch
is  ignored,  i.e.   the switch is only useful if it is used in combination
with the argument "@{b}GUI=off@{ub}".
You could use this switch if you just want to write the current system time
into  the  filetime  of  the  specified file, e.g.  to update the time just
before the system is powered off.


@{b}@{fg shine} Examples@{fg text}@{ub}

   @{b}SetSysTime S:.Date LOAD@{ub}

Use  this  commandline  to  load  the  time  from  the filetime of the file
"S:.Date"   and   open  the  dialog.   This  is  the  usual  entry  in  the
"startup-sequence".


   @{b}SetSysTime FILE S:.Date GUI=OFF SAVE@{ub}

The  current  system  time is written to the filetime of the file "S:.Date"
without opening the dialog.


   @{b}SetSysTime S:startup-sequence@{ub}

This will open the dialog and initialize it with the system time.
@endnode

@node WBStart "SetSysTime - Usage"

@{b}@{fg shine} Start from Workbench@{fg text}@{ub}

It  is  unusual but the tool might be started via the Workbench, if you add
an  icon to it.  You must nevertheless specify the file that should be used
to  read/write  the  time  from/to.  This is done by single @{i}clicking @{ui}on the
tools  icon and than @{i}double-clicking @{ui}on the icon of the file that should be
used for storing the time while the @{b}SHIFT@{ub}-key is pressed and hold down.

The  other  arguments  cannot  be passed to the tool so "@{b}SetSysTime@{ub}" always
opens the dialog window and always initializes the dialog with the filetime
of the specified file.

@endnode

@node Dialog "SetSysTime - Usage"

@{b}@{fg shine} Dialogwindow@{fg text}@{ub}

The  dialog is divided into two parts.  The left part is used to change the
date the right part is used to change the time.

At  the  top-left  corner  you  see a cycle-gadget used to chose the month.
Note that the year will increase if you cycle from December to January.

Right  of  the  month-gadget is a string-gadget with the current year.  You
can  change  the  year by selecting this gadget and entering the year using
the keyboard.

Below  these  gadgets  is  a  calendar-sheet  corresponding  to the current
selected month and year.  You could select the current day using the mouse.
There  are also displayed some days of the previous and the next month.  If
you  select  one  of  these  days you could switch to the next respectively
previous month.

At  the top-right corner you can see an analog clock displaying the current
time.   Using  the two sliders below the clock (one for the hour the second
one  for  the  minutes) you could set the time.  Note that the sliders work
from top to bottom, the lower the knob, the later the time.  If you release
the knobs after dragging them, they show the selected time.

At least there are three buttons at the bottom of the dialog.  From left to
right these are:  "@{b}Save@{ub}", "@{b}Use@{ub}", and "@{b}Cancel@{ub}".  All these buttons terminate
the  tool  and  close  the  dialog  but  the  further  action  performed is
different:
If  you  select "@{b}Save@{ub}" the selected date and time is used as current system
time and stored as filetime of the specified file.
If  "@{b}Use@{ub}"  is  selected  the selected date and time is also used as current
system time but the filetime of the specified file is @{b}not@{ub} changed.
At least "@{b}Cancel@{ub}" just terminates "@{b}SetSysTime@{ub}" without changing the current
system time and without changing the filetime of the specified file.


@{b}Hind@{ub}

If  you  add  this  tool  to your "startup-sequence" it will also be called
after  a  warmstart  ("Ctrl", "Amiga", "Amiga") and display the time of the
last boot, even if the system time is correct and shouldn't be changed (the
system  clock  is not reset by a warmstart).  Therefore you should @{i}"Cancel" @{ui}
the  dialog  after a warmstart, so the system time is not changed and stays
correct.

@endnode

